'''''Early Games''''' (aka '''''Early Games for Young Children''''') is a 1982 [[educational video game]] by Counterpoint Software and [[Springboard Software]], designed by John Paulson. The game contain a series of educational mini-games targeted at [[preschool]]ers and designed to teach basic math, language, and logic skills. It was part of the Skill Builder series, along with ''Fraction Factory'', ''Match Maker'', and ''Piece of Cake''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D0O_-ER3Z_gC&q=%22Early+Games%22+%22Springboard+%22+OR+%22counterpoint%22&pg=PA368|title=PC Mag|last=Inc|first=Ziff Davis|date=1984-12-11|publisher=Ziff Davis, Inc.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=amFQAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Piece+of+Cake%22+%22springboard%22|title=Teaching and Computers|date=1983-01-01|publisher=Scholastic|language=en}}</ref>

==Reception==
By April 6, 1985, ''Early Games'' had maintained an 18-week streak on the [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] charts for Top Educational Software.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MCQEAAAAMBAJ&q=%22Early+Games%22+%22Springboard+%22+OR+%22counterpoint%22&pg=PT25|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1985-04-06|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> After dropping off the charts the following week, it re-entered at #5 on April 20, 1985.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iyQEAAAAMBAJ&q=%22Early+Games%22+%22Springboard+%22+OR+%22counterpoint%22&pg=PT26|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1985-04-20|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> By August of that year, the game would spend a total of 36 weeks on the charts, then sitting at #3.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2CQEAAAAMBAJ&q=%22Early+Games%22+%22Springboard+%22+OR+%22counterpoint%22&pg=PT25|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1985-08-17|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> On May 3, 1986, the game re-entered the charts again, at #8.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1iQEAAAAMBAJ&q=%22Early+Games%22+%22Springboard+%22+OR+%22counterpoint%22&pg=PA39|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1986-05-03|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref>

''[[PC Magazine]]'' negatively compared ''Early Games for Young Children''{{'}}s graphics to those of competing title ''[[My Letters, Numbers, and Words]]'', through it praised the user friendliness of the former's menu, ultimately giving the program a score of 10.5/18. ''My Letters, Numbers, and Words'' received a score of 14.5/18 by comparison.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qURs4j9vKn4C&q=%22Early+Games%22+%22Springboard+%22+OR+%22counterpoint%22&pg=PA571|title=PC Mag|last=Inc|first=Ziff Davis|date=1983-10-01|publisher=Ziff Davis, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> ''[[Texas Monthly]]'' thought the game was "easy to operate", and added that both the game and ''[[Kids on Keys]]'' (from [[Spinnaker Software]]) were great options to serve as first experiences for young players to have with computers.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yisEAAAAMBAJ&q=%22Early+Games%22+%22Springboard+%22+OR+%22counterpoint%22&pg=RA1-PA198|title=Texas Monthly|date=1984-10-01|publisher=Emmis Communications|language=en}}</ref>

